  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity worldwide. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (such as funds from criminal activities like drug trafficking, corruption, or fraud) appear legitimate by disguising their true origin. This practice is illegal because it supports and enables criminal enterprises, undermines financial systems, and facilitates further illegal activities.\n\nMost countries have established laws and regulations to combat money laundering, often requiring financial institutions to implement measures such as customer due diligence, reporting suspicious transactions, and maintaining records. For example, in China, the Anti-Money Laundering Law explicitly prohibits money laundering and outlines strict penalties for individuals and entities involved in such activities. International organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) also set global standards to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.",
